post.description:
Using the bot creation wizard in the UI is the recommended approach to creating new bots as to ensure correct naming and configuration of filters and actions.

However, if a general pattern for creating a bot is known it's quite easy to take an existing bot configuration and use it as a template to programmatically create new bots. On a bot's overview page you can see the JSON configuration for the bot. You can use that JSON to create a new bot. Only the following keys will be used and all other keys ignored:

* name
* description
* severity
* category
* instructions
* hookpoints
* ondemand_enabled
* state
* schedule

This shows which keys will be used in an example bot.

```
{
 "category": "Security",
 // "owner_name": "Peter Snelgrove",
 "name": "Example bot",
 // "insight_id": null,
 // "resource_id": "divvybot:1:21",
 "severity": "low",
 // "detailed_logging": false,
 // "date_modified": "2018-01-16T15:14:16Z",
 "ondemand_enabled": true,
 // "source": null,
 "state": "PAUSED",
 // "valid": true,
 // "scope": [],
 // "owner": "divvyuser:1:",
 // "date_created": "2018-01-16T15:14:16Z",
 // "errors": [],
 "instructions": {
  "resource_types": [
   "instance"
  ],
  "groups": [],
  "filters": [
   {
    "config": {
     "cores": 2
    },
    "name": "divvy.filter.instance_cores_exceeds_threshold"
   }
  ],
  "schedule": null,
  // "schedule_description": null,
  "badges": [
   {
    "value": "wheat",
    "key": "grain",
    "$$hashKey": "object:2869"
   }
  ],
  "ondemand_enabled": true,
  "hookpoints": [],
  "actions": [
   {
    "run_when_result_is": true,
    "config": {
     "hours": 0
    },
    "name": "divvy.action.scheduled_stop"
   }
  ]
 },
 "description": "Demo for API documentation"
}
```

The uncommented keys represent the payload necessary to create an identical bot.

Note: use the Copy endpoint to copy an existing bot.
